class Solution:
    def backspaceCompare(self, s: str, t: str) -> bool:
        def get_next_valid_char(s, i):
            backspace_count = 0
            while i >= 0:
                if s[i] == '#':
                    backspace_count += 1
                elif backspace_count > 0:
                    backspace_count -= 1
                else:
                    return i
                i -= 1
            return -1

        i, j = len(s) - 1, len(t) - 1
        while i >= 0 or j >= 0:
            i = get_next_valid_char(s, i)
            j = get_next_valid_char(t, j)
            if i >= 0 and j >= 0 and s[i] != t[j]:
                return False
            if (i >= 0) != (j >= 0):
                return False
            i -= 1
            j -= 1
        return True
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n + m)
space complexity: O(1)
explanation: The solution uses two pointers to traverse both strings from the end, skipping characters based on the count of '#' encountered, thus comparing the final typed text in both strings efficiently.

